<controls:ChildWindow x:Class="VisualBF.About"
           xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml/presentation" 
           xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml" 
           xmlns:controls="clr-namespace:System.Windows.Controls;assembly=System.Windows.Controls"
           Width="400" Height="300" 
           Title="About">
    <Grid x:Name="LayoutRoot" Margin="2">
        <Grid.RowDefinitions>
            <RowDefinition Height="Auto" />
            <RowDefinition />
            <RowDefinition Height="Auto" />
        </Grid.RowDefinitions>
        <TextBlock Grid.Row="0" Text="Visual BF Interactive Interpreter" FontSize="20"/>
        <TextBlock Grid.Row="1" Margin="10" TextWrapping="Wrap">
            VisualBF started because someone suggested writing a Brainfuck interpreter would be a good contest. I took it as a challenge, and started working on my own. The contest never happened, but VisualBF did.<LineBreak />
            <LineBreak />
            To me, it was difficult to visualize what was actually happening in memory, so I drew the memory blocks. And the pointer. And the instruction pointer. It worked out nicely I think.<LineBreak />
            <LineBreak />
            Note: right-click the source panel for options.
        </TextBlock>
        <Button x:Name="CancelButton" Content="Close" Click="CancelButton_Click" Width="75" Height="23" HorizontalAlignment="Right" Margin="0,12,0,0" Grid.Row="2" />
    </Grid>
</controls:ChildWindow>